The Archetype System

The archetype system is the symbolic layer of Priority-Based Mindset Mapping.

It translates abstract priority configurations into recognizable human patterns drawn from mythology, folklore, social roles, literature, religion, and collective cultural memory.

An archetype is not a complete personality type. It is a compressed representation of a recurring priority geometry.

The Six-Priority Matrix

The system begins with three motivational domains:

Domain	Masculine priority	Feminine priority
Value	Dignity	Recognition
Stability	Security	Harmony
Resources	Acquisition	Comfort

Every person contains all six priorities in different proportions.

The masculine and feminine columns represent complementary motivational directions. They do not rigidly classify men and women.

The masculine direction tends to establish, defend, separate, venture outward, and obtain.

The feminine direction tends to reflect, connect, regulate, receive, cultivate, and convert conditions into lived experience.

How Archetypes Are Formed

An archetype is formed by pairing:

the strongest masculine priority,
with the strongest feminine priority.

There are three masculine priorities and three feminine priorities.

This creates nine basic pairings:


	Recognition	Harmony	Comfort
Dignity	Dignity and Recognition	Dignity and Harmony	Dignity and Comfort
Security	Security and Recognition	Security and Harmony	Security and Comfort
Acquisition	Acquisition and Recognition	Acquisition and Harmony	Acquisition and Comfort

Direction matters.

Dignity governing recognition is not the same configuration as recognition governing dignity.

Security governing harmony is not the same configuration as harmony governing security.

Acquisition governing comfort is not the same configuration as comfort governing acquisition.

Each of the nine pairings therefore has two directional expressions:

Nine pairings multiplied by two directions produces eighteen primary archetypes.

Governing and Supporting Priorities

The governing priority supplies the central motive.

The supporting priority determines how that motive is expressed.

For example:

Dignity governing recognition

The person establishes worth internally and expects that worth to be acknowledged.

This produces the King.

Recognition governing dignity

The person establishes social acknowledgment, position, or symbolic importance in order to embody and secure worth.

This produces the Queen.

Both archetypes concern value. Their direction differs.

The archetypes are therefore not simple combinations such as:

Dignity plus recognition equals authority.

The order matters:

Which priority is serving which?

Archetypes as Weighted Regions

The archetypes are not sealed boxes.

They are regions within a continuous priority landscape.

Two people may share the same archetype while differing substantially in:

the strength of their dominant priorities,
their overall masculine and feminine weighting,
their remaining four priorities,
personality,
intelligence,
culture,
morality,
emotional regulation,
learned strategies,
and stage of development.

A person may also lie between neighboring archetypes.

The purpose of the name is not to completely define the person. It is to make the dominant priority structure recognizable.

The Eighteen Archetypes
Dignity and Recognition
The King

Dignity governs recognition.

The King establishes value, standards, sovereignty, and rightful authority, then expects those things to be recognized.

The King asks:

Is my rightful standing being acknowledged?

Healthy expressions include leadership, responsibility, self-command, standards, and visible confidence.

The shadow includes tyranny, pride, humiliation sensitivity, loyalty tests, and confusing disagreement with disrespect.

The Queen

Recognition governs dignity.

The Queen embodies value through visibility, social position, reputation, symbolic presence, and acknowledgment.

The Queen asks:

Is my value being properly seen and reflected?

Healthy expressions include representation, charisma, cultural legitimacy, grace, and symbolic leadership.

The shadow includes vanity, rivalry, image control, status manipulation, and dependence on admiration.

Dignity and Harmony
The Gentleman

Dignity governs harmony.

The Gentleman maintains courtesy, restraint, and peaceful relations without surrendering self-respect.

The Gentleman asks:

How can I preserve both honor and relationship?

Healthy expressions include civility, fair dealing, composure, diplomacy, and principled restraint.

The shadow includes aloofness, moral superiority, excessive formality, emotional withdrawal, and hidden pride.

The Lady

Harmony governs dignity.

The Lady maintains relational grace, social calibration, decorum, and mutual respect.

The Lady asks:

How can dignity be expressed through proper relationship?

Healthy expressions include tact, diplomacy, mediation, social intelligence, and graceful boundary setting.

The shadow includes indirect aggression, social exclusion, concealed resentment, polite coercion, and suppression of necessary conflict.

Dignity and Comfort
The Patriarch

Dignity governs comfort.

The Patriarch establishes a household, institution, or domain according to standards of authority, responsibility, and provision.

The Patriarch asks:

Is this domain ordered in a way that reflects responsible authority?

Healthy expressions include provision, boundaries, stewardship, responsibility, standards, and long-term care for dependents.

The shadow includes authoritarianism, possessiveness, rigidity, domination, and treating others as extensions of the self.

The Matriarch

Comfort governs dignity.

The Matriarch establishes authority through the creation and regulation of a domain of care, nourishment, hospitality, and lived wellbeing.

The Matriarch asks:

Is the household or community being properly cared for under my direction?

Healthy expressions include hospitality, practical care, domestic authority, coordination, abundance, and protection of the household.

The shadow includes smothering, guilt-based control, possessive care, domestic despotism, and creating dependency through comfort.

Security and Recognition
The Champion

Security governs recognition.

The Champion confronts danger, protects the group, competes, or proves strength in a way that earns visible honor.

The Champion asks:

Have I proven that I can protect, endure, or win?

Healthy expressions include courage, defense, competition, morale building, decisive action, and public service.

The shadow includes glory seeking, manufactured conflict, recklessness, dependence on victory, and confusing performance with protection.

The Diva

Recognition governs security.

The Diva creates security through visibility, distinction, performance, audience loyalty, and control of public perception.

The Diva asks:

Am I visible and valued enough that my position remains secure?

Healthy expressions include commanding presence, artistic excellence, performance, cultural influence, and symbolic power.

The shadow includes attention dependency, rivalry, dramatic defensiveness, image obsession, and destabilizing situations to remain central.

Security and Harmony
The Guardian

Security governs harmony.

The Guardian protects the boundaries, people, institutions, or territory that make harmonious life possible.

The Guardian asks:

What must be defended so the group can remain intact?

Healthy expressions include vigilance, protection, duty, deterrence, boundaries, reliability, and willingness to confront threats.

The shadow includes suspicion, overprotection, authoritarian control, rigid policing, and treating every disturbance as danger.

The Mother

Harmony governs security.

The Mother creates safety through care, attachment, inclusion, soothing, and maintenance of relational bonds.

The Mother asks:

Are the vulnerable connected, supported, and emotionally safe?

Healthy expressions include nurturance, emotional safety, inclusion, care, repair, and relational continuity.

The shadow includes smothering, enmeshment, overaccommodation, controlling through care, and protecting others from necessary struggle.

Security and Comfort
The Steward

Security governs comfort.

The Steward maintains resources, routines, systems, and infrastructure so that comfort remains dependable.

The Steward asks:

What must be preserved so life remains sustainable?

Healthy expressions include maintenance, planning, conservation, reliability, financial prudence, and practical foresight.

The shadow includes hoarding, bureaucracy, excessive caution, resistance to innovation, and treating preservation as an end in itself.

The Hearthkeeper

Comfort governs security.

The Hearthkeeper protects the warm center of life: shelter, familiarity, nourishment, routine, atmosphere, and domestic continuity.

The Hearthkeeper asks:

How can the protected center remain warm, familiar, and undisturbed?

Healthy expressions include sanctuary, nourishment, domestic continuity, atmosphere, restoration, and everyday care.

The shadow includes territoriality, passive resistance, strategic helplessness, intolerance of disruption, and using fragility to control the environment.

Acquisition and Recognition
The Fool

Acquisition governs recognition.

The Fool ventures beyond the known in pursuit of experience, possibility, discovery, and new capability, even at the risk of appearing ridiculous.

The Fool asks:

What might become possible if I step beyond the map?

Healthy expressions include curiosity, experimentation, originality, creative freedom, play, and willingness to risk embarrassment.

The shadow includes recklessness, unfinished journeys, novelty addiction, confusing possibility with truth, and neglecting the route home.

The Trickster

Recognition governs acquisition.

The Trickster uses attention, humor, reversal, performance, ambiguity, and disruption to create access, freedom, opportunity, or advantage.

The Trickster asks:

How can I change what people notice so a new opening appears?

Healthy expressions include humor, improvisation, reframing, social intelligence, adaptive cunning, and exposure of rigid assumptions.

The shadow includes manipulation, deception, compulsive provocation, destabilization for its own sake, and becoming trapped in performance.

Acquisition and Harmony
The Builder

Acquisition governs harmony.

The Builder gathers people, tools, knowledge, materials, and cooperation in order to create something larger than the individual parts.

The Builder asks:

How can these people and resources be coordinated into capability?

Healthy expressions include organization, systems thinking, collaboration, institution building, production, and practical leadership.

The shadow includes instrumentalizing people, empire building, excessive control, expansion beyond humane scale, and reducing relationship to efficiency.

The Weaver

Harmony governs acquisition.

The Weaver creates opportunity by connecting people, information, resources, skills, and relationships.

The Weaver asks:

Which connections will allow new possibilities to emerge?

Healthy expressions include networking, matchmaking, alliance building, information flow, coalition formation, and social intelligence.

The shadow includes intrigue, gossip, covert manipulation, entanglement, gatekeeping, and indirect control over access.

Acquisition and Comfort
The Hunter

Acquisition governs comfort.

The Hunter leaves the protected center, tolerates uncertainty and hardship, and returns with resources, experience, or opportunity.

The Hunter asks:

What must be pursued and brought back?

Healthy expressions include provision, endurance, pursuit, risk tolerance, focus, and effectiveness outside familiar conditions.

The shadow includes predation, compulsive pursuit, inability to rest, unnecessary risk, and defining worth entirely through the chase.

The Gatherer

Comfort governs acquisition.

The Gatherer selects, collects, stores, curates, and arranges resources according to their usefulness for life and wellbeing.

The Gatherer asks:

What is worth collecting, preserving, and bringing into the living space?

Healthy expressions include curation, thrift, preparation, practical provisioning, selection, preservation, and resource awareness.

The shadow includes clutter, possessiveness, accumulation without purpose, overconsumption, and reluctance to venture beyond familiar sources.

The Role of Secondary Priorities

The remaining four priorities do not disappear.

They modify the archetype.

A Fool with high dignity may appear independent, defiant, and unwilling to seek permission.

A Fool with high harmony may explore collaboratively and bring people along.

A Fool with high security may become a calculated experimenter rather than a reckless adventurer.

A Fool with high comfort may prefer playful discovery over brutal frontier conditions.

The primary archetype identifies the central directional pairing.

Secondary priorities explain variation within that archetype.

This means the same archetype can appear in very different personalities.

Masculine and Feminine Weighting

A person can also be described by the overall weighting of the two columns.

A strongly masculine aggregate mindset gives greater combined precedence to:

dignity,
security,
acquisition.

A strongly feminine aggregate mindset gives greater combined precedence to:

recognition,
harmony,
comfort.

This does not determine which archetype a person occupies.

A person may belong to the Dignity and Harmony pairing while being:

dignity-led and strongly masculine,
harmony-led and strongly feminine,
or relatively balanced between the columns.

The archetype identifies the dominant relationship.

The masculinity or femininity score describes the larger directional balance of the whole map.

Archetypes and Personal Development

Every archetype contains both a mature and distorted expression.

The goal is not to replace one archetype with another.

The goal is to develop the neglected priorities that prevent the dominant configuration from becoming pathological.

The King may need harmony so authority does not become tyranny.

The Queen may need dignity so recognition does not become dependency.

The Guardian may need comfort so protection does not make life unbearable.

The Mother may need dignity and acquisition so care does not become enmeshment.

The Fool may need security so exploration produces something that survives.

The Trickster may need dignity so performance remains anchored in truth.

The Builder may need comfort so systems remain fit for human life.

The Hearthkeeper may need acquisition so preservation does not become stagnation.

Personal transformation can therefore be understood as a rebalancing of priority geometry.

How to Use the Archetype System

The system is most useful when asking:

Which masculine priority is strongest?
Which feminine priority is strongest?
Which one governs the relationship?
What is the person consistently trying to protect or increase?
What are they willing to sacrifice?
What kind of loss provokes them most strongly?
Which secondary priorities modify the primary pattern?
What mature and shadow expressions does the configuration permit?

The archetype should be treated as a provisional map.

It should never be used as proof that another person’s hidden motives are known with certainty.

A responsible interpretation sounds like:

This person appears to express a Guardian pattern because security repeatedly takes precedence and harmony is preserved through protection.

An irresponsible interpretation sounds like:

This person is a Guardian, so I know exactly what they think and how they will behave.

Current Status of the Names

The structure of the archetype system is more important than the names.

Some names already fit the model strongly:

King,
Queen,
Gentleman,
Lady,
Patriarch,
Matriarch,
Guardian,
Mother,
Fool,
Trickster,
Builder,
Weaver,
Hunter,
Gatherer.

Other names remain more provisional:

Champion,
Diva,
Steward,
Hearthkeeper.

The names should be refined through continued comparison with mythology, historical figures, literature, public personalities, and ordinary lived examples.

The objective is not to invent impressive labels.

The objective is to find symbols that make each priority geometry immediately intelligible.

Summary

The PBMM archetype system is built from:

three motivational domains,
six direct priorities,
two complementary columns,
nine masculine-feminine pairings,
and two directional expressions within each pairing.

This produces eighteen primary archetypes.

An archetype is a symbolic representation of a recurring aggregate priority geometry.

It is not the whole person.

It is a human-readable image of what their motivational structure most consistently places first.
